                            <comment id="16831179" author="stevel@apache.org" created="Wed, 1 May 2019 18:44:38 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thank you for tracking this down -this is is potentially quite serious.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As usual,  which AWS endpoint have you tested against, and which s3guard options. We have a very strict policy here. I&apos;ll be looking at this too, but I need to make sure you&apos;ve been running those tests too.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;One thing to consider: do we need these metrics at all with a move to on-demand tables? If the fix is more complex than what you&apos;ve proposed, I&apos;d be tempted to say &quot;let&apos;s cut it&quot;, but if everyone is confident that this is all the fix we need then it&apos;s not so critical&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16831449" author="prongs" created="Thu, 2 May 2019 07:19:05 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;There&apos;s&#160;three sides to this:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;S3Guard is not enableld for us and still it&apos;s creating these quantiles.&#160;Looking at the code also, there&apos;s no configuration guarding creation of these quantiles. So&#160;maybe&#160;we should&#160;guard that with a configuration?&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The quantiles once created are left aside without closing them. This causes &lt;tt&gt;MutableQuantiles&lt;/tt&gt;&#160;to never be Garbage collected since they are scheduled every second so the Scheduler Service Holds an instance of &lt;tt&gt;RolloverSample&lt;/tt&gt;, which holds an instance of &lt;tt&gt;MutableQuantiles&lt;/tt&gt;.&#160;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The scheduler is shared across all &lt;tt&gt;MutableQuantiles&lt;/tt&gt;&#160;and is single threaded. Scheduling is done via &lt;tt&gt;scheduleAtFixedRate&lt;/tt&gt;, which builds up a task queue, instead of &lt;tt&gt;scheduleAtFixedRate&lt;/tt&gt;, which doesn&apos;t.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;


&lt;p&gt;The patch I&apos;ve provided solves for 2. You still might want to take care of 1. Notice that because of the nature of the issue,&#160;a solution for 2 is still required with or without 1. &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HADOOP-16248&quot; title=&quot;MutableQuantiles leak memory under heavy load&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;HADOOP-16248&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;HADOOP-16248&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; takes care of 3.&#160;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16835590" author="stevel@apache.org" created="Wed, 8 May 2019 13:18:29 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Ok, checked out the patch. Looks good. I&apos;d just like to make sure we stop this coming back&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;a &lt;tt&gt;List&amp;lt;MutableQuantiles&amp;gt; quantileList&lt;/tt&gt; of quantiles to stop should be built up in a list the way the later counters are collected; there&apos;s no need to define unique fields&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;so teardown would be &lt;tt&gt;quantileList.foreach(MutableQuantiles::stop);&lt;/tt&gt; .&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;and the &lt;tt&gt;quantiles()&lt;/tt&gt; method could actually add it to the list after registration&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Do you feel like extending your patch and testing locally to see it works for you? thanks&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16835672" author="stevel@apache.org" created="Wed, 8 May 2019 15:12:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Actually I&apos;m +1 as is; let&apos;s worry about tuning it if/when more quanties are added.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Rajat -is there an email address I can use to declare you as the author of the patch, so that github will wire up your contribution?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16835783" author="fabbri" created="Wed, 8 May 2019 17:46:35 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Agreed, +1&#160;this simple patch stopping the quantiles on FS close. Also wanted to say nice work on this Jira &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=prongs&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;prongs&quot;&gt;prongs&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16836224" author="prongs" created="Thu, 9 May 2019 09:14:05 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=stevel%40apache.org&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;stevel@apache.org&quot;&gt;stevel@apache.org&lt;/a&gt; Yes, please link up with the profile&#160;&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/prongs&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://github.com/prongs&lt;/a&gt;&#160; (prongs@apache.org, rajatgupta59@gmail.com).&#160;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Agreed that we can make it a &lt;tt&gt;List&lt;/tt&gt;&#160;but I went with two independent variables since I had to test fast. Plus, looking at the pattern, I&apos;d safely assume any person adding the third quantile will automatically end up making&#160;that change.&#160;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16836668" author="stevel@apache.org" created="Thu, 9 May 2019 20:20:36 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;+1&lt;br/&gt;
committed to branch-3.1+. Didn&apos;t take in 3.0 but if someone does a patch there, I&apos;ll add it too. I suspect it was the addition of a new quantile in 3.2 which amplified the problem&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
